 due to the problem\n\nA cyber attack targeting Leicester City Council has led to some street lights\nbeing stuck on all day. The attack crippled the authority's services seven\nweeks ago and led to confidential documents being published online by the\nhackers, including rent statements and applications to buy council houses.\n\nA ransomware group of online criminals was behind the attack, which happened\non Thursday, March 7, and completely closed down the city council's IT\nsystems. And now a new problem has been revealed.\n\nBeaumont Leys resident Roger Ewens, 65, noticed the street lights in his road\nwere on constantly and asked the city council why. He was surprised when he\nreceived a reply blaming the cyber attack for affecting the \"central\nmanagement system\" and leading to the streetlights \"misbehaving\".\n\nREAD MORE: Leicester City Council says confidential documents including\npassport info shared online in cyber attack\n\nHe was told in the email he received today (Monday) that the problem should be\nsorted out by the end of next week. He told LeicestershireLive: \"The lights in\nmy area have been burning away all day and all night, so it's got to be\ncosting a lot.\n\nSIMILAR ARTICLES TO THIS\n\nPowered by\n\nCity centre offices being eyed up for flats\n\n14 Comments\n\nLeader of Leicester\u2019s Conservative Party returns to Labour fold 18 months\nafter quitting\n\n33 Comments\n\nTruth behind Leicester City\u2019s psychological title stumble as Enzo Maresca\n\u2018process\u2019 analysed\n\n9 Comments\n\nLeicester City have 'new solution' up their sleeve \u2013 but Enzo Maresca doesn't\nneed it yet\n\n14 Comments\n\nHinckley Road travel live updates as collision closes off main route\n\nComments\n\nDog attacks man trying to save his pet from mauling\n\n6 Comments\n\nTime running out to apply for voter ID in the upcoming police and crime\ncommissioner elections\n\n2 Comments\n\nThird boy arrested after Leicester stabbing\n\nComments\n\nMan charged a